entry.title: Add VRR availability flag
entry.content:
This change adds a ui base feature flag, VariableRefreshRateAvailable,

for indicating whether the variable refresh rate feature is available

on the device. The flag will be set from the chromeos configuration

file for devices which are participating in the VRR experiment study.

The flag is not exposed via chrome://flags.



This change also adds a parameter to the EnableVariableRefreshRate

feature flag which determines whether the availability flag should be

ignored. The parameter defaults to true so that users who override the

VRR setting from chrome://flags can use it freely. Experimental groups

in the Finch study will obey the availability setting as intended.

entry.title: Use distinct methods for policy rules in sandbox
entry.content:
The sandbox library on Windows includes a complex rules engine to

allow proxied functions to evaluate their arguments. Details of

this engine leak out of the sandbox interface via the AddRule()

method which allows specification of a subsystem and semantics.



In practice only four actions are currently supported: allowing

access to files or pipes, allowing Dlls to load under CIG and

setting up GDI hooks for Win32 lockdown.



This CL removes the generic AddRule method from sandbox_policy.h

and replaces it with several more-specific functions, allowing

deletion of the SubSystem enum. This should allow for simplification

of the internals of the rules-engine without exposing these

changes to the rest of Chromium.



No functional changes.

entry.title: CSS highlight painting: further optimise offset mapping
entry.content:
One of the most expensive highlight painting operations is converting

DOM offsets to canonical text offsets.



This CL improves performance by switching to DOM offsets for

comparing the target fragment to the markers, meaning the fragment

is converted once and markers are only converted if they overlap

the fragment in DOM space. The existing MarkerRangeMappingContext

is modified to use DOM offsets and its use is enforced everywhere

where offset mapping is done for markers.



Based on an original proposal by dazabani@,

https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/4014023,

heavily modified to rebase and optimize further.



Other changes include:

* Clamp the marker offsets to the text fragment in DOM space before

mapping.

* Do not try to compute overflow for empty marker lists.

* Testing for MarkerOffsetMappingContext

* Clean up some use of Member<>

entry.title: Android: Map default screen orientation to USER
entry.content:
Previously, default was mapped to UNSPECIFIED, which the documentation

seems to imply should cause the activity to inherit the orientation mode

of the activity below it in the task stack, defaulting to USER if there

is none. However, in my testing of our TWA app, this is not the case in

recent Android versions. In the best case (Android 12), UNSPECIFIED

behaves the same as USER regardless of the underlying activity's

orientation mode. In the worst case (Android 13 & 14), UNSPECIFIED

results in the display retaining whatever orientation mode it was in

prior to switching to the TWA. That means that returning to the TWA

from the launcher (which uses NOSENSOR) results in it no longer being

possible to rotate the TWA. This is one of the top complaints for our

app.



With this change, the TWA can always be rotated in the manner expected

when using the default orientation mode. TWA apps can still specify a

different orientation mode using

TrustedWebActivityIntentBuilder.setScreenOrientation.

Update the minimum, maximum, and default timeout values for webauthn

requests to be more generous and meet

accessible experience if they want to make use of longer timeouts, and

that the default is accessible.

entry.title: Update ImageFlip logic and clean up OpenXrApiWrapper
entry.content:
It looks like the existing logic to always flip the image when using

shared buffers may actually be a DirectX quirk. It appears as though

some Android OpenXR implementations previously ignored this value; but

we've found some that seem to actually be respecting it where our

content is now rendered upside down.



This CL fixes the issue by delegating the decision of whether the flip

is needed to the specific OpenXrGraphicsBinding that is in-use. Moving

this logic down here led to a bit of a yak-shave moving some related

methods where the OpenXrApiWrapper was really doing some work that the

GraphicsBindings should be responsible for, and led to a few minor

cleanups as a result:



1) IsUsingSharedImages (which the D3D11 binding needed access to) was

essentially just querying state that the GraphicsBinding knew about.

This method was thus moved onto the graphics binding. The only caller

of this method on the OpenXrApiWrapper also had access to the

graphics binding and can thus just call it directly, thus removing

that method from the OpenXrApiWrapper altogether.

2) In moving IsUsingSharedImages, it looks like

`ReleaseColorSwapchainImages` was the only remaining place in

OpenXrApiWrapper that actually knew about the Mailbox settings on

SwapChainInfo when shared images were in use, so that method was

also moved into the GraphicsBinding to avoid leaking some of that

information where not necessary.

3) The `PrepareViewConfigForRender` which needed to query whether or

not the image was flippable didn't actually need to be in

OpenXrApiWrapper, and indeed it felt a little weird to keep it

there and query a method about if the image should be flipped.

Thus the method was moved onto the graphics binding to better

encapsulate both the decision about whether or not the image should

be flipped and how to go about flipping it. This method also only

ever returned XR_SUCCESS and thus was changed to a `void` method.

Apart from minor changes to the passed in parameters and the return

type, the comment about flipping the image was updated.
